PART 2: HISTORICAL EVIDENCE - PRIMARY SOURCES & VERIFICATION

This section provides verified primary source documentation that
systematically refutes White Legend claims. Evidence comes from Spanish
chroniclers, Indigenous sources, church records, legal documents,
archaeological remains, and modern genetics.

1\. The Requerimiento at Cajamarca (November 16, 1532)

**Verified:** Father Vicente de Valverde read the Requerimiento to
Atahualpa in Cajamarca\'s main plaza

**Primary Sources:**

-   **Francisco de Xerez** *(Pizarro\'s secretary, eyewitness):
    Verdadera Relación de la Conquista del Perú* (1534) - first
    published account

-   **Pedro Pizarro, Miguel de Estete:** Corroborating accounts from
    witnesses present

**What the Requerimiento Said:**

\"On the part of the King, Don Fernando, and of Doña Juana, his
daughter, Queen of Castile and León, subduers of the barbarous nations,
we their servants notify and make known to you, as best we can, that the
Lord our God, Living and Eternal, created the Heaven and the Earth, and
one man and one woman.\"

\"Of all these nations God our Lord gave charge to one man, called St.
Peter, that he should be Lord and Superior of all the men in the world.
One of these Pontiffs who succeeded that St. Peter as Lord of the world
made donation of these isles and Tierra-firme to the aforesaid King and
Queen and to their successors.\"

\"But, if you do not do this, and maliciously make delay in it, I
certify to you that, with the help of God, we shall powerfully enter
into your country, and shall make war against you in all ways and
manners that we can, and shall subject you to the yoke and obedience of
the Church and of their Highnesses; we shall take you and your wives and
your children, and shall make slaves of them.\"

**The Translation Catastrophe:**

-   **Interpreter: Felipillo** (from Tumbes, Tallán ethnicity)

-   **Background:** Learned Spanish during brief 1527-1528 visit to
    Spain, learned Quechua as second language from coastal natives

-   **William Robertson\'s assessment:** \'little acquainted with the
    idiom of the Spanish tongue, and incapable of expressing himself
    with propriety in the language of the Inca\'

-   **Language barriers:** Quechua lacked vocabulary for Trinity, faith,
    holy spirit. Reportedly translated \'God is three in one\' as \'God
    said three and one is four\'

-   **Deliberate mistranslation:** Multiple chroniclers document
    Felipillo deliberately mistranslated to ensure Atahualpa\'s death
    (he desired one of the Inca\'s wives). Executed by Almagro\'s orders
    in 1535 for repeated treasons

**Atahualpa\'s Verified Responses:**

-   \"I will be no man\'s tributary\"

-   Regarding the book: Asked why it didn\'t speak to him when he held
    it to his ear

2\. Demographic Collapse - The Numbers

**Peru Population Estimates:**

-   **Pre-contact (1520):** 5-9 million (Noble David Cook: 9 million)

-   **1620 (100 years later):** 670,000

-   **Mortality rate:** 90-93% population decline within one century

-   **W. George Lovell:** \'Greatest destruction of lives in human
    history\' - approximately 1 in 5 people on Earth at the time

**Americas-Wide Collapse:**

-   **Pre-contact:** 54-100 million (conservative: 54M)

-   **1650:** 5-6 million

-   **Overall mortality:** 89-95% within 150 years

**Causes (Synergistic):**

-   **Disease:** Smallpox, measles, typhus, influenza (Old World
    pathogens)

-   **Forced labor:** Encomienda, mita (especially mining), weakened
    immune systems

-   **Violence:** Direct warfare, punitive expeditions, executions

-   **Social disruption:** Family separation, reduced reproduction,
    psychological trauma

-   **Malnutrition:** Resource extraction, agricultural disruption

3\. Khipu Destruction - Epistemological Genocide

**What Were Khipus?**

-   Sophisticated knotted string record-keeping system used by Inca
    Empire

-   Recorded: census data, tribute obligations, genealogies, calendars,
    possibly narratives

-   **Created/maintained by specialist class:** khipukamayuqs (khipu
    keepers)

-   **Modern research:** Gary Urton (Harvard Khipu Database - 751
    specimens), Sabine Hyland - demonstrate mathematical/administrative
    sophistication

**Spanish Dependence (1530s-1580s):**

-   **Spanish colonizers initially** *relied on* khipukamayuqs and
    khipus for 50 years to administer empire

-   Could not collect tribute or conduct census without indigenous
    record-keeping

-   Garcilaso de la Vega documented Spanish officials requiring
    khipukamayuqs to decode records

**Systematic Destruction (1583):**

-   **Third Council of Lima (1583):** Officially banned khipus as
    \'idolatrous\'

-   **Polo de Ondegardo documentation:** \"Spanish burned the khipu and
    punished the Indian\"

-   **Sources report:** \'Spaniards\...proceeded to burn all the khipus
    and kill all the Khipu-Kamayuq\'s they could find\'

-   **Timing:** Once colonial administration stabilized with European
    alphabetic writing, indigenous record-keepers became disposable

**Surviving Evidence:**

-   600-750 khipus survive in museums worldwide (Harvard database: 751
    specimens)

-   Major collections: American Museum of Natural History, Museum für
    Völkerkunde Berlin, Peruvian institutions

-   Living communities in Peru/Bolivia still maintain khipus for
    counting livestock, Catholic festival calendars

-   Inkawasi khipus: First direct archaeological link between khipus and
    specific goods recorded

4\. Sexual Violence - Extensive Documentation

**Primary Sources:**

***A. Bartolomé de las Casas (1542)***

*Brief Account of the Destruction of the Indies* - written directly to
King Charles V:

\"The Spaniards have shown not the slightest consideration for these
people, treating them (and I speak from first-hand experience, having
been there from the outset) not as brute animals---indeed, I would to
God they had done and had shown them the consideration they afford their
animals---so much as piles of dung in the middle of the road.\"

\"After the wars and the killings had ended, when usually there survived
only some boys, some women, and children, these survivors were
distributed among the Christians to be slaves. The Indians were totally
deprived of their freedom and were put into the harshest, fiercest, most
horrible servitude and captivity which no one who has not seen it can
understand.\"

***B. Felipe Guaman Poma de Ayala (c.1615)***

-   1,189-page illustrated chronicle with 398 drawings documenting:

    -   Priests sexually exploiting Indigenous women in confessional

    -   Encomenderos taking multiple Indigenous women as concubines

    -   Systematic pattern of sexual coercion across colonial hierarchy

***C. Inquisition Records***

-   Thousands of cases documenting clerical sexual abuse

-   **Legal category created:** *sollicitatio ad turpia* (priests
    exploiting confession for sexual advances)

-   **Timeline:** Pope Paul IV granted prosecution power 1558, extended
    to Spanish territories 1561, Peru\'s Inquisition established 1570

-   **Example:** 1587 Lima Inquisition official \'arraigned on 216
    charges of sexual misconduct and found guilty on five counts; he was
    later promoted to higher Church office.\' One Jesuit reportedly
    \'solicited\' more than 100 women

***D. Archaeological Evidence***

-   **Puruchuco-Huaquerones study** *(Murphy et al., American Journal of
    Physical Anthropology, 2010, PMID: 20333713):*

    -   258 adults from two cemeteries near Lima (1470-1540)

    -   Post-contact cemetery: 25.0% perimortem trauma vs. 13.0%
        pre-contact (statistically significant)

    -   \'Several injuries from 57AS03 are consistent with documented
        cases of injuries from firearms and 16th Century European
        weapons\'

    -   2011 study: 242 children showed statistically significant
        increases in cranial trauma post-contact - \'intensification of
        violence and lethality that may have affected the children\'

***E. DNA Evidence - Quantifying Generations of Rape***

**Largest genetic study:** *23andMe, 50,281 participants, American
Journal of Human Genetics, 2020, PMID: 32589925*

**Extreme Sex Bias in Admixture:**

-   **Central America:** 15.60 African women per 1 African man
    contributing genes

-   **Northern South America:** 17.17 African women per 1 African man

-   **Indigenous ancestry:** 28.04 Native American women per 1 Native
    American man (Central America)

-   **Note:** These ratios exist despite slave ship records showing over
    60% male captives

**European Ancestry (Inverse Pattern):**

-   **British Caribbean:** 25.53 European men per 1 European woman in
    genetic contributions

-   **Study states explicitly:** \'An Americas-wide African female
    sex-bias can be attributed to known accounts of rape of enslaved
    African women by slave owners and other sexual exploitation\'

-   **Methodology:** Compared X chromosome vs. autosomal ancestry, plus
    Y chromosome (paternal) vs. mitochondrial (maternal) haplogroups

-   **Finding:** Males across Latin America consistently show European Y
    chromosomes but African or Indigenous mitochondrial DNA - definitive
    proof of European male/Indigenous or African female admixture as
    dominant pattern

**Academic Authorities:**

-   **Karen Vieira Powers:** *Women in the Crucible of Conquest* -
    documents systematic sexual exploitation

-   **Irene Silverblatt:** *Moon, Sun, and Witches* - analyzes gender
    and colonial power in Peru

-   **Cambridge World History of Violence:** Chapter on legitimized
    colonial violence

5\. The Encomienda System - Institutionalized Slavery

**What White Legend Claims:** Encomienda resembled European
feudalism---reciprocal obligations between lords and vassals

**What Evidence Shows:**

-   **System:** Spanish colonizers granted Indigenous labor and tribute
    from specific communities

-   **Theory:** Encomenderos \'protected\' Indigenous people, taught
    Christianity

-   **Reality:** Forced labor extraction, minimal protection, widespread
    abuse

**Contemporary Spanish Critics:**

-   **Antonio de Montesinos (1511):** \'By what right or justice do you
    keep these Indians in such a cruel and horrible servitude? Are these
    not men?\'

-   **Las Casas (1542):** Encomenderos worked Indigenous people \'to
    death in gold mines and other labors\...more than a million souls
    perished unjustly\'

-   **Domingo de Santo Tomás (1550):** \'\[The encomienda is\] the most
    terrible slavery and captivity in which men ever found
    themselves\...infinite number of these Indians perished and still
    are perishing without faith, without sacraments\'

**Demographic Impact:**

-   **Hispaniola:** 3 million (1494) → 15,000 (1550) - 99.5% mortality
    in 56 years

-   **Cuba:** 112,000 (1511) → 600 (1555) - 99.5% mortality in 44 years

-   **Puerto Rico:** 600,000 (1508) → 3,000 (1555) - 99.5% mortality in
    47 years

**The Mita System (Peru):**

-   Based on Inca mit\'a (reciprocal labor), transformed into forced
    mine labor

-   **Potosí silver mines:** Required 13,500+ workers annually
    (one-seventh of adult male population from designated provinces)

-   **Death rate:** Historic documents indicate \'more than 8 million
    workers likely died\' in colonial mines

-   **Causes:** Silicosis, mercury poisoning, mine collapses,
    exhaustion, malnutrition

-   **Duration:** 1573-1825 (252 years) - continued 148 years AFTER
    Peruvian independence through hacienda systems until 1969

6\. Legal Protections vs. Reality - The Gap

**White Legend Emphasizes:**

-   **Laws of Burgos (1512):** First colonial labor regulations

-   **New Laws (1542):** Abolished Indigenous slavery, restricted
    encomiendas

-   **Sublimis Deus (1537):** Papal bull declaring Indigenous peoples
    rational, enslavement mortal sin

**Reality of Enforcement:**

-   **Colonial resistance:** Gonzalo Pizarro rebelled against New Laws
    (1544), killed Viceroy Blasco Núñez Vela (1546), proving how
    seriously encomenderos took humanitarian regulation threats

-   **Laws modified:** 1545 modifications allowed encomienda
    inheritance, undermining reform

-   **Distance factor:** 3-6 month communication lag between Spain and
    colonies enabled systematic violation

-   **Economic incentives:** Spanish Crown profited from mining (20%
    quinto real), created perverse incentive against enforcement

**Indigenous Perspective on \'Protection\':**

-   **Indigenous scholars note:** \'By the year 1537 a fact situation of
    domination had already been created. The bull Sublimis Deus could do
    nothing to change forty years of destruction and institutionalized
    domination\'

7\. Contemporary Spanish Critics - Proof of Abnormality

The existence of sustained Spanish criticism from 1511 onwards proves
colonial brutality exceeded acceptable bounds even by 16th-century
standards.

**Key Critics & Their Fates:**

-   **Antonio de Montesinos (1511):** Ordered back to Spain after
    sermon, convinced King Ferdinand to pass Laws of Burgos. Later
    murdered by Spanish officer in 1540 for protecting Indigenous
    people---tombstone refers to him as martyr

-   **Bartolomé de las Casas:** Faced continuous opposition from
    encomenderos and colonial authorities throughout 50+ year career

-   **Victorián de Villava:** Accused of \'crime of lèse-patrie and
    lèse-majesté\' in 1796 for calling mita \'temporary slavery\'

**The Valladolid Debate (1550-1551):**

-   **Unprecedented:** King Charles V halted conquests pending
    investigation

-   **Participants:** Las Casas (Indigenous peoples have natural rights)
    vs. Sepúlveda (natural slaves)

-   **Significance:** \'First moral debate in European history to
    discuss rights and treatment of colonized people\'

-   **Outcome:** No official winner declared, but Charles V continued
    favoring Las Casas\'s position in practice

**School of Salamanca (1530s-1540s):**

-   **Francisco de Vitoria:** Questioned legality of Spanish conquest,
    argued Indigenous peoples had natural rights to lands and
    sovereignty

-   **Relectio de Indis:** Contended conquest violated natural law,
    rejected papal donation and Requerimiento as legal justifications

-   **Too controversial:** Not published during lifetime, but influenced
    Valladolid judges

-   **Legacy:** Now considered foundational to international law

PART 3: DEBATE PREPARATION - ARGUMENTS & REFUTATIONS

This section provides point-by-point refutations of common White Legend
arguments with citations ready for debate.

Argument 1: \'Mestizaje Proves Benevolence\'

**White Legend Claim:**

\'Spanish colonialism practiced inclusive expansion through mestizaje
(racial mixing), unlike British/Dutch/Belgian exclusionary colonialism.
This proves Spanish tolerance and integration.\'

**Refutation:**

-   **1. Mestizaje Resulted From Systematic Rape**

    -   **DNA evidence:** 28.04 Native American women per 1 Native
        American man contributed genes (23andMe study, 50,281
        participants, 2020)

    -   **Pattern:** European Y chromosomes + Indigenous mitochondrial
        DNA = systematic sexual violence by European men

    -   **Study conclusion:** \'African female sex-bias can be
        attributed to known accounts of rape\...and other sexual
        exploitation\'

-   **2. Mestizaje Created Hierarchy, Not Equality**

    -   **Casta system:** Classified people by racial mixture---16+
        categories determining legal status, economic access, social
        position

    -   **Hierarchy:** Peninsular (Spain-born) \> Criollo (colony-born
        Spanish) \> Mestizo (Spanish-Indigenous) \> Indigenous \>
        African

    -   **Marisol de la Cadena:** \'De-Indianization\'---mestizaje
        required abandoning Indigenous identity for social mobility

    -   **Modern continuation:** \'Mejorar la raza\' (improve the race)
        through whitening---Marco Avilés: \'pruning family tree
        branches, cutting roots, forgetting where you come from\'

-   **3. Comparisons Are Misleading**

    -   **Population difference:** Peru had 5-9M Indigenous people
        (1520), North America outside Mexico had 5-8M total. 90% of 9M
        leaves more survivors than 90% of 5M

    -   **Economic model:** Spanish needed Indigenous labor alive
        (mining, agriculture). English wanted land (displacement
        westward)

    -   **Both genocidal:** 80-90% mortality rates across Americas
        regardless of colonial power. Different mechanisms, same outcome

Argument 2: \'More Indigenous People Survived in Latin America\'

**White Legend Claim:**

\'Look at population numbers---more Indigenous people survived Spanish
colonization than English colonization. This proves Spanish treatment
was more humane.\'

**Refutation:**

-   **Same Percentage Mortality:** Peru lost 90-93% (9M → 670K in 100
    years). North America lost 80-90% (different timeline). Similar
    mortality rates

-   **Different Starting Numbers:** Mesoamerica/Andes had 40+ million
    pre-contact (dense civilizations). North America had 3-8 million
    (dispersed). 10% survival of larger population = more absolute
    survivors

-   **Math, Not Mercy:** 10% of 40M = 4M survivors. 10% of 5M = 500K
    survivors. Same percentage, different absolute numbers

Argument 3: \'Spain Had Protective Laws\'

**White Legend Claim:**

\'Spain passed Laws of Burgos (1512), New Laws (1542), papal bull
Sublimis Deus (1537). No other colonial power demonstrated such moral
concern for Indigenous peoples.\'

**Refutation:**

-   **Laws Were Systematically Violated:**

    -   **Colonial rebellion:** Gonzalo Pizarro killed Viceroy Blasco
        Núñez Vela (1546) for attempting to enforce New Laws

    -   **Laws modified:** 1545 modifications allowed encomienda
        inheritance, undermining reforms

    -   **Distance factor:** 3-6 month communication lag between Spain
        and colonies enabled systematic violation

    -   **Economic incentives:** Spanish Crown profited (20% quinto real
        from mining), creating perverse incentive against enforcement

-   **Gap Between Law and Reality:**

    -   **Domingo de Santo Tomás (1550):** \'\[The encomienda is\] the
        most terrible slavery and captivity in which men ever found
        themselves\'

    -   **Demographic evidence:** Despite \'protective\' laws, 90-93%
        population decline occurred

    -   **Indigenous perspective:** \'By 1537 a fact situation of
        domination had already been created. Sublimis Deus could do
        nothing to change forty years of destruction\'

-   **White Legend Methodology Error:**

    -   Substitutes legal texts for lived reality

    -   Emphasizes intentions over outcomes

    -   Ignores enforcement gap

Argument 4: \'Spain Brought Civilization\'

**White Legend Claim:**

\'Pre-Columbian Americas had human sacrifice, cannibalism, endemic
warfare. Spanish brought Christianity, technology, civilization. This
justified conquest as humanitarian intervention.\'

**Refutation:**

-   **1. Inca Civilization Was Advanced:**

    -   **Infrastructure:** 40,000 km road network (Qhapaq Ñan),
        suspension bridges, agricultural terracing, aqueducts

    -   **Administration:** Sophisticated khipu record-keeping system
        for census, tribute, logistics

    -   **Architecture:** Machu Picchu, Cuzco,
        Sacsayhuamán---earthquake-resistant stonework

    -   **Agriculture:** Domesticated potato, quinoa, freeze-dried food
        storage (chuño)

    -   **Medicine:** Successful skull surgery (trepanation),
        quinoa/coca medicinal use

-   **2. Spanish Destroyed This Civilization:**

    -   **Garcilaso de la Vega (mestizo chronicler):** \'The Spaniards
        exhausted the natural wealth---the llama herds, the fertilizer,
        everything---entirely in a few decades, whereas wise Inca policy
        had husbanded them and made them fructify\'

    -   **Khipu destruction:** Third Council of Lima (1583) banned
        sophisticated record-keeping system, burned khipus, persecuted
        specialists

    -   **Reducciones:** Forced 2+ million Indigenous people into
        planned towns (GeoPACHA Project, 2023), disrupting agricultural
        systems

-   **3. \'Civilization\' Was Cover for Extraction:**

    -   **Pizarro\'s admission:** \'insatiable greed for gold\'
        motivated conquest

    -   **Colonial economy:** Built entirely on extracting silver
        (Potosí: 8+ million deaths), gold, resources

    -   **Christianity as justification:** Requerimiento shows religious
        rhetoric used to legitimize conquest and enslavement

-   **4. European Violence:**

    -   **Simultaneously:** Spanish Inquisition burning people at stake,
        European wars of religion, witch trials

    -   **Irony:** \'Civilizing\' rhetoric from continent practicing
        systematic religious persecution

Argument 5: \'This Is Ancient History\'

**White Legend Claim:**

\'These events happened 500 years ago. Why does it still matter?
Focusing on colonial past prevents moving forward.\'

**Refutation:**

-   **1. Colonial Hierarchies Persist Today:**

    -   **Peru employment:** Indigenous Peruvians need 80% more job
        applications than non-Indigenous for same position

    -   **Life expectancy:** Indigenous Peruvians die 20 years younger
        than non-Indigenous

    -   **2022 protests:** 46 of 49 protesters killed were in Indigenous
        regions

    -   **Wealth concentration:** Spanish-descended elites dominate
        economy, politics, media

-   **2. White Legend Enables Contemporary Dispossession:**

    -   **Bolsonaro (Brazil):** Called Indigenous \'cavemen,\' opened
        Yanomami lands to miners (570 children died)

    -   **Peru:** \'Terruqueo\' labels Indigenous activists as
        terrorists, justifying suppression

    -   **Chile:** Mapuche movements framed as \'narcoterrorism\'

    -   **Pattern:** Colonial-era justifications updated for modern
        extraction and displacement

-   **3. Timeline of Continuity:**

    -   **Mita:** 1573-1825 (252 years), continued through hacienda
        systems until 1969---148 years AFTER independence

    -   **Indigenous rights:** Peru ratified ILO Convention 169 in 1993,
        but didn\'t implement prior consultation until 2011---190 years
        after independence

    -   **Not ancient:** These systems operated within living memory

-   **4. Historical Memory Shapes Present Politics:**

    -   **Vox (Spain):** Explicitly celebrates Reconquista and conquest,
        gained 52 parliamentary seats

    -   **Madrid Charter:** Transnational far-right coordination using
        colonial memory

    -   **Textbooks:** Spanish museums and curricula still omit
        Indigenous perspectives

    -   **Consequence:** Inaccurate history enables contemporary
        injustice

PART 4: RHETORICAL STRATEGIES FOR DEBATES

**Effective Debate Tactics:**

-   **1. Lead With Spanish Sources**

    -   Strategy: Use contemporary Spanish critics (Las Casas,
        Montesinos, Santo Tomás) to prove brutality exceeded
        16th-century norms

    -   Example: \'Let\'s not rely on modern historians. Here\'s what
        Spanish friar Domingo de Santo Tomás said in 1550\...\'

    -   Impact: Undermines \'modern bias\' arguments by showing Spanish
        people condemned colonialism as it happened

-   **2. Emphasize Quantitative Evidence**

    -   DNA ratios (28.04:1 female-to-male genetic contribution)

    -   Mortality rates (90-93% in Peru within 100 years)

    -   Archaeological trauma studies (25% perimortem trauma rate
        post-contact vs. 13% pre-contact)

    -   Impact: Numbers are harder to dismiss than qualitative
        descriptions

-   **3. Flip Comparative Arguments**

    -   When opponent says: \'But the English were worse\...\'

    -   Response: \'You\'re right that both were genocidal. That\'s
        exactly my point---we shouldn\'t defend either. The question
        isn\'t who was worse, but why we\'re still lying about
        colonization 500 years later.\'

    -   Impact: Refuses comparative relativism, focuses on truth vs.
        falsehood

-   **4. Connect History to Present**

    -   Always follow historical claims with contemporary consequences

    -   Example: \'This isn\'t just history. When Bolsonaro calls
        Indigenous people cavemen and opens their lands to miners, 570
        children die. Colonial apologetics have body counts.\'

    -   Impact: Prevents dismissal as \'ancient history,\' shows stakes

-   **5. Expose Methodological Flaws**

    -   Point out White Legend\'s systematic errors:

        -   Substitutes legal texts for reality (laws existed but
            weren\'t enforced)

        -   Emphasizes intentions over outcomes (humanitarian rhetoric
            vs. genocidal results)

        -   Uses comparative relativism to deflect (why us more than
            them?)

        -   Impact: Discredits entire revisionist approach

-   **6. Pre-Empt Bad-Faith Arguments**

    -   Anticipate and address weak objections:

        -   \'You\'ll hear that Las Casas exaggerated. But his account
            convinced King Charles V to pass the New Laws in 1542---the
            Spanish Crown found him credible enough to risk colonial
            revolt.\'

        -   \'They\'ll say disease caused most deaths. That\'s partially
            true---but Spanish forced labor weakened immune systems,
            malnutrition increased susceptibility, and social disruption
            prevented care. Disease and exploitation worked
            synergistically.\'

        -   Impact: Shows you\'ve anticipated objections, strengthens
            credibility

**Common Fallacies to Watch For:**

-   **Ad hominem:** \'You\'re just perpetuating the Black Legend\'

    -   **Response:** \'I\'m citing Spanish sources---Las Casas,
        Montesinos, Santo Tomás. They lived through this.\'

-   **Whataboutism:** \'What about British/Dutch/Belgian colonialism?\'

    -   **Response:** \'All colonial powers committed atrocities. That
        doesn\'t make any of them benevolent.\'

-   **Presentism:** \'You\'re judging them by modern standards\'

    -   **Response:** \'Spanish people in 1511 called this cruel and
        horrible servitude. I\'m judging them by THEIR standards.\'

-   **False equivalence:** \'Indigenous people had human sacrifice too\'

    -   **Response:** \'Ritual sacrifice in religious context is
        qualitatively different from systematic forced labor killing 8+
        million in mines. And conquistadors weren\'t motivated by
        stopping sacrifice---Pizarro admitted insatiable greed for
        gold.\'

